      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a chemical process between amino acids and reducing sugars that causes browning and flavor development in foods. This reaction typically begins around 140°C to 165°C (284°F to 329°F) and accelerates significantly above 170°C (338°F). It is distinct from caramelization, which involves the pyrolysis of sugars and requires higher temperatures. Understanding these parameters is crucial for achieving the desired texture and taste in cooked dishes.",
